8
00:00:50,753 --> 00:00:59,302
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samasambuddhasa.

9
00:00:59,323 --> 00:01:03,567
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble, and fully self-awakened one.

10
00:01:07,632 --> 00:01:17,316
So this evening, we were going to leave not self for a while and tackle some of the questions that have come in.

11
00:01:18,640 --> 00:01:20,022
Let's get the paper upside down first.

12
00:01:20,043 --> 00:01:20,644
Here we are.

13
00:01:20,665 --> 00:01:20,825
Good.

14
00:01:20,864 --> 00:01:21,186
Very good.

15
00:01:22,465 --> 00:01:25,769
Now, the first one is about anger.

16
00:01:25,790 --> 00:01:29,956
Is all anger to be avoided and purified?

17
00:01:30,176 --> 00:01:32,558
So I'm thinking of abuses of power and injustice.

18
00:01:33,459 --> 00:01:45,957
I was feeling angry at the government for suggesting the public fundraise for the NHS when they already pay it through taxation, yet find money for other things when pressed.

19
00:01:48,486 --> 00:01:52,036
So this is a question about anger.

20
00:01:52,537 --> 00:02:00,618
So really all you have to ask yourself is, you know, when you're angry, what's your state of mind?

21
00:02:00,719 --> 00:02:04,689
I mean, are you open to the other person's viewpoints?

22
00:02:05,058 --> 00:02:11,687
Are you really concerned with winning the argument and not really seeking the truth?

23
00:02:13,491 --> 00:02:16,354
What's actually guiding the anger?

24
00:02:17,036 --> 00:02:20,782
Now, often the case of anger sits on fear.

25
00:02:22,403 --> 00:02:31,318
Your identity, your views, your opinions have been upset, they've been attacked, and the response is to get rid of the enemy.

26
00:02:31,906 --> 00:02:47,754
So the Buddha is quite clear that any form of anger is going to distort our thinking and will eventually end up creating even more anger, one way or the other, even if we overwhelm the person.

27
00:02:47,735 --> 00:02:55,067
and they run away with their tail between their legs, they will be thinking about ways in which to get back to us.

28
00:02:55,527 --> 00:02:59,633
So anger is, in Buddhist understanding, it's basically a no-no.

29
00:03:00,155 --> 00:03:03,920
Now, one example that is given here is that

30
00:03:04,372 --> 00:03:08,617
How is Jesus viewed in Buddhism turning the moneylenders out of the temple?

31
00:03:08,998 --> 00:03:16,527
Well, of course, in Christian thinking, they do often translate that as righteous anger.

32
00:03:17,049 --> 00:03:19,350
But in Buddhism, they don't say righteous anger.

33
00:03:20,353 --> 00:03:22,555
But what there is is assertiveness.

34
00:03:22,716 --> 00:03:27,140
So that distinction between aggression and assertiveness.

35
00:03:27,121 --> 00:03:41,364
Now, if one is coming from a state of inner equanimity and yet knows what ought to be said, then that anger becomes translated into a force, into a form which supports you.

36
00:03:42,545 --> 00:03:47,373
And of course, because you're based on equanimity and wisdom, you have the power for that.

37
00:03:47,894 --> 00:03:49,217
And the other people feel that.

38
00:03:50,459 --> 00:03:59,598
As soon as you're angry, they also feel your fear because if they come back at you and they see that there's a slight bit of fear in you, then they know they're winning the argument.

39
00:04:00,118 --> 00:04:06,611
But when you're being assertive, when you're being correct, when you're standing your ground,

40
00:04:06,929 --> 00:04:12,026
You are open to the other person's argument and you may be nuanced.

41
00:04:12,086 --> 00:04:13,812
I mean, you may be affected by it.

42
00:04:13,854 --> 00:04:14,616
It's not a problem.

43
00:04:15,138 --> 00:04:17,968
But you are assertive about your particular position.

44
00:04:19,838 --> 00:04:32,757
This goes back to this business of free speech, where there was a time a couple of years back, two or three years back maybe, where I think I've mentioned this, where they had the right to insult.

45
00:04:33,218 --> 00:04:35,341
Well, nobody has a right to insult anybody.

46
00:04:35,822 --> 00:04:41,610
It was a very harsh way of expressing the fact that you can be assertive about your opinion.

47
00:04:41,589 --> 00:05:02,721
about your perspective and I know that the other person's not going to be happy with it but that's their problem not yours yeah so I think that distinction is is very valid and it stops you getting into fights awful situations that can come back at you

48
00:05:05,906 --> 00:05:10,690
Again, does the Buddhist path separate from all these things?

49
00:05:10,791 --> 00:05:14,574
Is it all seen as samsara, not to be engaged with?

50
00:05:14,915 --> 00:05:21,321
And that's the other thing that you sort of, because you don't want to get angry, you don't get engaged.

51
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:26,065
Well, I mean, that's the other negative side of not being engaged.

52
00:05:26,125 --> 00:05:33,653
But if you are coming from a point of wisdom, a point of compassion, then, of course,

53
00:05:33,632 --> 00:05:36,817
your behavior will engage you.

54
00:05:37,377 --> 00:05:41,221
And the Buddha had no problem engaging in serious situations.

55
00:05:41,882 --> 00:05:47,990
You know, his people and the Kaliya, who owned the other side of the river, were going to fight about water rights.

56
00:05:48,630 --> 00:05:54,038
And he went up, you know, and he said to them, what's more precious, the blood in your veins or the water

57
00:05:54,017 --> 00:06:13,697
in the river and that sort of cooled them down a bit you know uh and uh kings would come to him for advice his advice was always you know to seek uh to seek the way to peace not seek the way to war so um

58
00:06:16,192 --> 00:06:22,949
And then they go on to say, also, I've been feeling sad about all the deaths and the families that have been left bereaved.

59
00:06:23,589 --> 00:06:26,336
Am I right in thinking that

60
00:06:28,814 --> 00:06:44,916
I don't know whether Salzburg, that's the book she's reading, Sharon Salzburg, Loving Kindness, which is still a sort of basic classic on that area, is saying that that is no longer compassion, but sadness.

61
00:06:46,338 --> 00:06:50,404
And is compassion that we need, is it compassion that we need to develop?

62
00:06:50,425 --> 00:06:50,625
Yes.

63
00:06:52,326 --> 00:06:57,774
I think we've also touched upon this, the distinction between grief and sorrow.

64
00:06:57,754 --> 00:07:09,492
Sorrow is the ability to feel another person's pain and empathy, and it requires us, it impedes us to find a way of helping.

65
00:07:10,153 --> 00:07:17,343
Even if we can't help, at least we can send our good wishes or influence somebody else to help them.

66
00:07:17,382 --> 00:07:23,711
But that's not to be confused with grief, which is the pain we feel when we lose somebody

67
00:07:24,045 --> 00:07:26,670
whom we're dependent on for our personal happiness.

68
00:07:27,310 --> 00:07:28,754
It's a different thing.

69
00:07:30,255 --> 00:07:41,295
The sensations, the feelings can be very similar, but they have different roots.

70
00:07:46,016 --> 00:07:51,062
The Buddha himself is also known as the Mahakaruniko, he's the great compassionate one.

71
00:07:51,403 --> 00:08:00,853
Because after all, he spent his life trying to save us from suffering, trying to save all people from suffering, which was a big task, let's face it.

72
00:08:03,836 --> 00:08:08,581
So yes, anger, generally speaking, is a no-no.

73
00:08:09,161 --> 00:08:15,567
You want to try and redirect the energy towards assertiveness.

74
00:08:17,675 --> 00:08:18,997
We do need compassion.

75
00:08:19,016 --> 00:08:24,747
We need to be in touch with people, feel what they feel as a resonance.

76
00:08:25,028 --> 00:08:31,980
Now, obviously, you can't feel what another person feels, but you can resonate with it and do what we can to help.

77
00:08:33,403 --> 00:08:38,873
Trembling in the heart, that's what the Buddha says, a sort of trembling in the heart when you see somebody suffering.

78
00:08:42,126 --> 00:09:10,075
okay so the next one is um by the way if questions come up out of this just email me yeah email me are my thoughts and feelings dependent on my physical body if i had a different body would i have different thoughts etc um well of course uh many of them are dependent by me that's why you know we we keep in the evening we go on about sickness aging and death we're very concerned with the body

79
00:09:10,561 --> 00:09:37,311
uh it definitely brings up a lot of anxiety and a lot of all the other stuff uh it's through the body of course we're in contact with the material world outside with the phenomena with the with the yeah with the with with the material world outside through our senses and it's and it's that which creates this inner phenomenal uh experience so obviously if you if you're deaf then you know that

80
00:09:37,712 --> 00:09:43,922
That dimension of experiencing things as something that you can hear is not there for you.

81
00:09:44,462 --> 00:09:48,629
So the body has a direct effect on the mind.

82
00:09:49,350 --> 00:09:54,837
But then, of course, there are many things that affect the mind-heart which are not directly coming from the body.

83
00:09:56,541 --> 00:10:02,590
Well, we've just talked of one really, our bodies anyway, is that when we see somebody who's in a bad state,

84
00:10:03,092 --> 00:10:04,054
We want to help them.

85
00:10:04,395 --> 00:10:06,059
It might not be a physical bad state.

86
00:10:06,080 --> 00:10:08,264
It might be a mental one, but you want to help.

87
00:10:09,226 --> 00:10:11,993
So not everything comes from the body.

88
00:10:12,654 --> 00:10:14,820
If you had a different body, would you have different thoughts?

89
00:10:15,942 --> 00:10:18,368
It very much depends, really.

90
