I've forgotten that particular remark until just today, actually.

100
00:11:01,327 --> 00:11:03,191
So yes, uh, different bodies.

101
00:11:03,350 --> 00:11:09,899
I mean, obviously, um, if your body's disabled, that's a, that's a different situation too.

102
00:11:10,500 --> 00:11:17,669
So, uh, having the body we have brings its, its own, um, mental situations.

103
00:11:17,730 --> 00:11:27,123
You know, if you've got a healthy athletic body that never falls ill, and that's very different from a person who's continuously weak, falls ill, et cetera, breaks their bones and so on.

104
00:11:27,964 --> 00:11:28,585
So yes.

105
00:11:31,432 --> 00:11:32,634
Don't wish for another body.

106
00:11:32,754 --> 00:11:33,394
That's what I say.

107
00:11:33,414 --> 00:11:34,756
Just be happy with the one we've got.

108
00:11:34,797 --> 00:11:35,957
You never know what you're going to get.

109
00:11:39,282 --> 00:11:51,274
The next one is I've tried the death contemplation, breathing in as the body's last breath, only for around five minutes of time, tagged on to the normal meditation.

110
00:11:51,294 --> 00:11:55,720
First, I was shocked just how attached I was to everything, absolutely everything.

111
00:11:56,154 --> 00:12:01,764
Then I realized it was to this body and sense experiences resulting from it.

112
00:12:02,605 --> 00:12:10,136
Then when I applied it to wandering thoughts and worries, it put these worries and thoughts into perspective and the realization how unimportant they are.

113
00:12:11,057 --> 00:12:15,565
Should I use this when I'm really upset or worried?

114
00:12:18,312 --> 00:12:43,053
i think that's what uh the contemplation of death does it puts things in a in a in a wider perspective um and you get different priorities uh even now through this uh covered thing you know where we're having to isolate or then you know it's making i think a lot of people experience life in a different way

115
00:12:43,793 --> 00:12:47,322
And then he might be thinking, why am I rushing around all the time?

116
00:12:47,464 --> 00:12:50,913
What's the point of earning all that money if I'm going to be stressed out all the time?

117
00:12:51,676 --> 00:12:53,922
I'm hoping that's what's happening anyway.

118
00:12:54,695 --> 00:13:00,923
So the contemplation of death puts life into a different perspective.

119
00:13:01,543 --> 00:13:04,386
And one of the things is to see what a treasure it is.

120
00:13:05,087 --> 00:13:07,451
And one wants to live fully within the present moment.

121
00:13:09,472 --> 00:13:16,000
So when one turns to one's worries, you think, well, what's that in terms of death?

122
00:13:16,501 --> 00:13:21,427
So little worries or these superficial things might just fade away.

123
00:13:21,408 --> 00:13:34,124
But you have to be careful about using these techniques not to feel what the heart wants to express, especially if the feeling is a strong one, if you've got sadness or anxiety.

124
00:13:35,586 --> 00:13:43,956
Doing that sort of thing, you can fall into the error of what's been called spiritual bypassing, which is just another way of saying suppressing.

125
00:13:43,936 --> 00:13:55,144
So often, for instance, in the tradition, a great emphasis is put on impermanence, anicca, anicca, everything's changing, everything's changing.

126
00:13:55,832 --> 00:14:08,288
And what happens is you're looking or you're feeling, say, some anxiety, and you're sort of stepping back, but stepping back in the wrong way and looking at it and saying, oh, yeah, it's all arising and passing away.

127
00:14:08,307 --> 00:14:09,229
It's all arising and passing away.

128
00:14:09,249 --> 00:14:15,376
But you're not feeling the intensity of that anxiety, and therefore the heart can't cure itself.

129
00:14:15,817 --> 00:14:17,379
It just goes back into the system.

130
00:14:17,399 --> 00:14:20,743
You just get just as neurotic as you were before.

131
00:14:21,263 --> 00:14:25,869
So don't forget that it's anicca, anatta, but it's also dukkha, right?

132
00:14:26,429 --> 00:14:30,195
And that's in the discourse on establishing this right awareness.

133
00:14:30,956 --> 00:14:38,586
The Buddha's constantly putting us in, to feel feelings in feelings, to feel mental states in mental states.

134
00:14:38,605 --> 00:14:39,586
It's the same as a room.

135
00:14:39,846 --> 00:14:46,635
It's the difference between being outside, looking in through the window, or at the doorway, or on top of the room, or under the room.

136
00:14:46,956 --> 00:14:50,240
It's completely different when you actually go into the room.

137
00:14:50,221 --> 00:14:55,690
And that's when you actually experience the room as an internal experience.

138
00:14:55,711 --> 00:14:58,575
And that's what you're doing with these emotions, with these mental states.

139
00:14:59,096 --> 00:15:01,561
You want to get into them and feel them as they are.

140
00:15:02,101 --> 00:15:10,996
Then when you're inside feeling them as they really are, that's when you can also begin to recognize that it's actually changing.

141
00:15:11,381 --> 00:15:23,315
And that's when you're getting down to that level of the different things that make up a feeling, you know, the heaviness, the burning, and all that sort of stuff.

142
00:15:23,335 --> 00:15:24,596
So be careful about that.

143
00:15:24,996 --> 00:15:34,067
I mean, that's when you get teachers saying that, you know, you need psychotherapy before you go to vipassana.

144
00:15:35,128 --> 00:15:37,331
Or you need psychotherapy after you've done vipassana.

145
00:15:38,491 --> 00:15:41,034
